Voronoi Diagram¶

Source: wikipedia

  • "In mathematics, it is a partition of a plane into regions close to each of a given set of objects."
  • Up to 3 variables:
    • X axis (quantitative variable)
    • Y axis (quantitative variable)
    • Voronoi cell color (qualitative variable)
  • Useful to:
    • Highlight spatial patterns
    • Identify distribution areas
  • Limitations:
    • Hard to compare voronoi cells

import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

dataset_url = "https://davidmegginson.github.io/ourairports-data/airports.csv"
df = pd.read_csv(dataset_url, sep=',')

world = gpd.read_file(gpd.datasets.get_path('naturalearth_lowres'))
spain_area = world[world.name == 'Spain']
In [3]:
df = df[df.iso_region.str.startswith('ES')]
In [4]:
geometry = [Point(xy) for xy in zip(df.longitude_deg, df.latitude_deg)]
gdf = gpd.GeoDataFrame(df, geometry=geometry)
gdf = gdf.set_crs('EPSG:4326')
In [5]:
# Setup the Voronoi axes; this creates the Voronoi regions
ax = gplt.voronoi(gdf[['geometry']], figsize=(25, 25))
ax = gdf.plot(ax=ax)
gplt.polyplot(spain_area, ax=ax)
